Hello,

I have this issue (I almost created a solution xD). But, it's true that Swift APIs can have arbitrary metadata, and these metadata are labeled by X-Object-Meta-<name> and not X-Container-Meta-<name>.

The functionality to handle such data is already implemented at [openstack/objectstorage/v1/objects/results.go#L284](https://github.com/gophercloud/gophercloud/blob/4f6d1451acac9260a6901451e146b2bee4742bb5/openstack/objectstorage/v1/objects/results.go#L284)

For containers, there is no such metadata as per the documentation: [Object Storage API - Containers.](https://docs.openstack.org/api-ref/object-store/#show-container-details-and-list-objects).

Regarding the issue of having characters in object names that could violate the [ISO-8859-1](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO/IEC_8859-1) or the [None ASCII in headers](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc7230#section-3.2) rule, this is already implemented in Openstack, refere to this example:
```bash
[stack@undercloud (overcloudrc) ~]$ openstack object set aldokimi-test file.txt --property "Filename=??-F??l??.txt"
Cannot set property Filename to non-ascii value
2025-11-08 01:06:33,742 ERROR [object_store_v1.py:586] Cannot set property Filename to non-ascii value
```
But, if you use the swift API directly to create metadata for an object, it will allow you to add any characters you want, so I propose to add a function to the HTTP wrapper, this function will replace ISO-8859-1/UTF-8 non-printable characters with '?', refer to the code bellow:
```go
func FilterHTTPHeader(value string) string {
	var builder strings.Builder
	builder.Grow(len(value))

	for _, r := range value {
		if r == '\t' || (r >= 32 && r <= unicode.MaxASCII) {
			builder.WriteRune(r)
		} else {
			builder.WriteRune('?')
		}
	}
	return builder.String()
}
```
If the idea is approved, I will create a PR and post it,

Thanks,

issueDTO.description:
Neat little feature from Scala. You can write a type `A&B`, i.e. something that is both `A` and `B` at the same time

This would be mostly useful for mixins, where you could do

```
???mixin A {}
???mixin B {}
???struct Foo { include A }
???struct Bar { include A include B }

func foo(x: A&B) { ... }
```

and `foo` could accept `Bar` but not `Foo` instances

Using this + union types (which Aria already has), you can probably write weird complex type expressions, but that's the only downside I can think of?

Before Angular 20, it was possible to read Resource.value() without any issues even when the value was not yet available - you just got undefined.

So code like this worked:

```
explicitEffect([resource.value], ([value] => {
  if (value) {
     foo();
 }
}); 
```

However, in NG20. Reading value() when the value is not available (when hasValue() is not true), it will throw the exception.

So this code is not possible anymore i guess. 

in effect() we can do:

```
effect(() =>  {
    if (resource.hasValue()) {
         ...resource.value()...
  }
}); 
```

but there is probably not any way how to do that in explicitEffect/effectOnceIf or am i missing something?

Because:
- we need to react not only to hasValue() but value() as well
- value() is evaluated eagerly (to be passed to callback)  



Possible workaround:
- use computed signal inside explicit effect




```

safeValue = computed(()=> this.resource.hasValue() ? this.resource.value() : null);
explicitEffect([safeValue], ([safeValue] => {
  if (safeValue) {
     foo();
 }
}); 
```



Suggestions:
- highly opiniated, probably soiling your api, however... 

 allow to pass resource to "signals array" - and extract value (T | undefined) - or entire state of resource-

```
explicitEffect([resource], ([resource: {value: T | unc, isLoading: boolean,..} ] => {
  if (resource.value) {
     foo();
 }
}); 
```

